yle="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we believe </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the BBC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> shou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ld help provide access to the arts </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the widest possible public. It should help cultural organisations make their collections accessible to people via imaginative programming.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The BBC has already shown how it can take some of the finest music performances</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> theatrical productions into our homes, experiences which for some would be prohibitively expensive. More of this should happen so that people across the country realise th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ere is fabulous talent in all parties of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, not just </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">With headquarters in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, Salford and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Glasgow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the BBC is in a strong position to make a difference regionally so that access to arts and culture can be shared across the country.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Public</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> service broadcasting should provide for quality programming which would not be made on commercial channels. There should be a mix of popular programming and those which target smaller, niche audiences. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC is good at sharing different voices and opini</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ons, not just those of the critics and professionals, and should continue to do so to ensure that viewers continue to feel part of the BBC. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Above all standards in news and documentaries must be maintained; with the BBC retaining its role as provider of i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n-depth, reliable and well-researched content.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How well has the BBC performed…?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The move to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Salford</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has resulted in a tangible difference in terms of regional arts coverage. Among national media outlets, the BBC is outperforming many others in its attemp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t to break down the traditional London-centric bias.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is still much more to be achieved. BBC Salford has started to develop strong relationships with some of the leading cultural organisations in the North - this approach is welcomed and should be bu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ilt upon. The museums and galleries across the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> house the most amazing treasures from across the world - collections which could be made far more accessible through the medium of television and radio.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Should the BBC’s output and services be provided t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">o any greater or lesser degree for particular audiences? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">should be truly national in remit, covering stories from around the country and giving equal weight to issues/stories from the regions as well as the capital. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC is in a class all of its own in terms of children’s television and should continue to expand this. There could well be advantages in developing commercial partnerships with public and private sector partners so that the characters and stories broug</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ht to life on television can be translated into exhibitions (look at the success of the Harry Potter experience) which tour the country and potentially generate new income streams which can be shared between partners through ticket sales and merchandise. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">here is a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">large </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">market for such attractions in Europe, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Far East</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the Middle East &amp; China</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Maybe there are opportunities for further collaboration between the BBC and different publicly funded organisations. The BBC might consider working more closely w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ith the NHS for example to tailor programmes for those who suffer from conditions like dementia.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">hat role should the BBC play in developing technology and new ways of distributing content?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC is full of some of the most </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">creative and technical talent which exists in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> today</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. It would be madness for the BBC not to channel this into developing new </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ways of delivering and distributing content</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. It is the technological development which is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">incredibly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">important in terms of w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">idening access as it is the language of the next generation.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Maybe in this area and others, the BBC has a role to play in training and mentoring, sharing its knowledge and experience with others in the region.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Fiona </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Philpott</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Director of Exhibitions &amp; Design, National Museums Liverpool</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>